Preheat the oven to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9.

Chop the @potatoes{600%g} into 2cm wide wedges (peeling optional).

Pop the wedges onto a large (lined) #baking tray{}. Toss with half the @Thai Style Spice Mix{1%sachet}, @salt{to taste}, @pepper{to taste} and a drizzle of @oil{to taste}. Spread out in a single layer.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-35%minutes}. Turn the tray halfway through.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

Lay the @Irish Chicken Breast{320%g} onto another lined baking tray. Drizzle with oil and season with remaining Thai spice, salt and pepper. Roast on the middle shelf of the oven until cooked through, ~{25-30%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging. Chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

> TIP: Notice a stronger smell from your chicken? Don't worry, this is normal due to packaging used to keep it fresh.

Trim the @Green Beans{150%g}.

When the chicken has been cooking for ~{15%minutes}, spread the green beans out on the tray alongside the chicken. Drizzle with oil then season with salt and pepper. Return to the oven for the remaining cooking time, ~{10-15%minutes}.

In a small #bowl{}, mix the @Ketjap Manis{1%sachet}, @Sweet Chilli Sauce{1%sachet} and @Peanut Butter{1%sachet}.

> Little chef's TIP: Kids can help to mix together the sauces.

Divide the roast potatoes, green beans and chicken between plates. Serve with the peanut sauce alongside for dipping.